[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] One major practical drawback is its $O(b^{d})$ space complexity where d is the depth of the shallowest solution (the length of the shortest path from the source node to any given goal node) and b is the branching factor (the maximum number of successors for any given state).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] In practical travel-routing systems, it is generally outperformed by algorithms that can pre-process the graph to attain better performance, as well as by memory-bounded approaches; however, A* is still the best solution in many cases.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart, Nils Nilsson and Bertram Raphael of Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) first published the algorithm in 1968.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] It can be seen as an extension of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* achieves better performance by using heuristics to guide its search.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm terminates once it finds the shortest path to a specified goal, rather than generating the entire shortest-path tree from a specified source to all possible goals.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* was created as part of the Shakey project, which had the aim of building a mobile robot that could plan its own actions.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Nils Nilsson originally proposed using the Graph Traverser algorithm for Shakey's path planning.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Graph Traverser is guided by a heuristic function *h*(*n*), the estimated distance from node n to the goal node: it entirely ignores *g*(*n*), the distance from the start node to n.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Bertram Raphael suggested using the sum, *g*(*n*) + *h*(*n*).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart invented the concepts we now call admissibility and consistency of heuristic functions.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* was originally designed for finding least-cost paths when the cost of a path is the sum of its costs, but it has been shown that A* can be used to find optimal paths for any problem satisfying the conditions of a cost algebra.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The original 1968 A* paper contained a theorem stating that no A*-like algorithm could expand fewer nodes than A* if the heuristic function is consistent and A*'s tie-breaking rule is suitably chosen.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* is an informed search algorithm, or a best-first search, meaning that it is formulated in terms of weighted graphs: starting from a specific starting node of a graph, it aims to find a path to the given goal node having the smallest cost (least distance travelled, shortest time, etc.).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] It does this by maintaining a tree of paths originating at the start node and extending those paths one edge at a time until the goal node is reached.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] At each iteration of its main loop, A* needs to determine which of its paths to extend.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] It does so based on the cost of the path and an estimate of the cost required to extend the path all the way to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] where n is the next node on the path, *g*(*n*) is the cost of the path from the start node to n, and *h*(*n*) is a heuristic function that estimates the cost of the cheapest path from n to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The heuristic function is problem-specific.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Typical implementations of A* use a priority queue to perform the repeated selection of minimum (estimated) cost nodes to expand.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] This priority queue is known as the *open set*, *fringe* or *frontier*.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] At each step of the algorithm, the node with the lowest *f*(*x*) value is removed from the queue, the f and g values of its neighbors are updated accordingly, and these neighbors are added to the queue.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm continues until a removed node (thus the node with the lowest f value out of all fringe nodes) is a goal node.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The f value of that goal is then also the cost of the shortest path, since h at the goal is zero in an admissible heuristic.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm described so far only gives the length of the shortest path.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] To find the actual sequence of steps, the algorithm can be easily revised so that each node on the path keeps track of its predecessor.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] After this algorithm is run, the ending node will point to its predecessor, and so on, until some node's predecessor is the start node.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] As an example, when searching for the shortest route on a map, *h*(*x*) might represent the straight-line distance to the goal, since that is physically the smallest possible distance between any two points.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] For a grid map from a video game, using the Taxicab distance or the Chebyshev distance becomes better depending on the set of movements available (4-way or 8-way).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic h satisfies the additional condition *h*(*x*) ≤ *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) for every edge (*x*, *y*) of the graph (where d denotes the length of that edge), then h is called monotone, or consistent.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] With a consistent heuristic, A* is guaranteed to find an optimal path without processing any node more than once and A* is equivalent to running Dijkstra's algorithm with the reduced cost *d'*(*x*, *y*) = *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) − *h*(*x*).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm has real-world applications.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] In this example, edges are railroads and h(x) is the great-circle distance (the shortest possible distance on a sphere) to the target.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm is searching for a path between Washington, D.C., and Los Angeles.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] There are a number of simple optimizations or implementation details that can significantly affect the performance of an A* implementation.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The first detail to note is that the way the priority queue handles ties can have a significant effect on performance in some situations.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If ties are broken so the queue behaves in a LIFO manner, A* will behave like depth-first search among equal cost paths (avoiding exploring more than one equally optimal solution).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] When a path is required at the end of the search, it is common to keep with each node a reference to that node's parent.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] At the end of the search, these references can be used to recover the optimal path.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If these references are being kept then it can be important that the same node doesn't appear in the priority queue more than once (each entry corresponding to a different path to the node, and each with a different cost).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A standard approach here is to check if a node about to be added already appears in the priority queue.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If it does, then the priority and parent pointers are changed to correspond to the lower-cost path.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A standard binary heap based priority queue does not directly support the operation of searching for one of its elements, but it can be augmented with a hash table that maps elements to their position in the heap, allowing this decrease-priority operation to be performed in logarithmic time.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Alternatively, a Fibonacci heap can perform the same decrease-priority operations in constant amortized time.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm, as another example of a uniform-cost search algorithm, can be viewed as a special case of A* where ⁠ $h(x)=0$ ⁠ for all *x*.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] General depth-first search can be implemented using A* by considering that there is a global counter *C* initialized with a very large value.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Every time we process a node we assign *C* to all of its newly discovered neighbors.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] After every single assignment, we decrease the counter *C* by one.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Thus the earlier a node is discovered, the higher its ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Both Dijkstra's algorithm and depth-first search can be implemented more efficiently without including an ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value at each node.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] On finite graphs with non-negative edge weights A* is guaranteed to terminate and is *complete*, i.e. it will always find a solution (a path from start to goal) if one exists.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] On infinite graphs with a finite branching factor and edge costs that are bounded away from zero ( ${\textstyle d(x,y)>\varepsilon >0}$ for some fixed $\varepsilon$ ), A* is guaranteed to terminate only if there exists a solution.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A search algorithm is said to be *admissible* if it is guaranteed to return an optimal solution.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic function used by A* is admissible, then A* is admissible.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Call a node *closed* if it has been visited and is not in the open set.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] We *close* a node when we remove it from the open set.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A basic property of the A* algorithm, which we'll sketch a proof of below, is that when ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate (lower bound) of the true distance from the start to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] So when the goal node, ⁠ g ⁠, is closed, ⁠ $f(g)$ ⁠ is no more than the true distance.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, it is no less than the true distance, since it is the length of a path to the goal plus a heuristic term.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Now we'll see that whenever a node ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ P ⁠ be an optimal path from the start to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ p ⁠ be the last closed node on ⁠ P ⁠ for which ⁠ $g(p)$ ⁠ is the true distance from the start to ⁠ p ⁠ (the start is one such vertex).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The next node in ⁠ P ⁠ has the correct ⁠ g ⁠ value, since it was updated when ⁠ p ⁠ was closed, and it is open since it is not closed.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The definitive study of the optimal efficiency of A* is due to Rina Dechter and Judea Pearl.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] They considered a variety of definitions of **Alts** and **P** in combination with A*'s heuristic being merely admissible or being both consistent and admissible.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The most interesting positive result they proved is that A*, with a consistent heuristic, is optimally efficient with respect to all admissible A*-like search algorithms on all "non-pathological" search problems.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Roughly speaking, their notion of the non-pathological problem is what we now mean by "up to tie-breaking".
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] This result does not hold if A*'s heuristic is admissible but not consistent.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] In that case, Dechter and Pearl showed there exist admissible A*-like algorithms that can expand arbitrarily fewer nodes than A* on some non-pathological problems.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Optimal efficiency is about the *set* of nodes expanded, not the *number* of node expansions (the number of iterations of A*'s main loop).
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] When the heuristic being used is admissible but not consistent, it is possible for a node to be expanded by A* many times, an exponential number of times in the worst case.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] In such circumstances, Dijkstra's algorithm could outperform A* by a large margin.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] While the admissibility criterion guarantees an optimal solution path, it also means that A* must examine all equally meritorious paths to find the optimal path.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] To compute approximate shortest paths, it is possible to speed up the search at the expense of optimality by relaxing the admissibility criterion.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Oftentimes we want to bound this relaxation, so that we can guarantee that the solution path is no worse than (1 + *ε*) times the optimal solution path.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] This new guarantee is referred to as *ε*-admissible.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] As a heuristic search algorithm, the performance of A* is heavily influenced by the quality of the heuristic function ${\textstyle h(n)}$ .
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic closely approximates the true cost to the goal, A* can significantly reduce the number of node expansions.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, a poor heuristic can lead to many unnecessary expansions.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] In the worst case, A* expands all nodes ${\textstyle n}$ for which ${\textstyle f(n)=g(n)+h(n)\leq C^{*}}$ , where ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ is the cost of the optimal goal node.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Suppose there is a node ${\textstyle N'}$ in the open list with ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , and it's the next node to be expanded.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Since the goal node has ${\textstyle f(goal)=g(goal)+h(goal)=g(goal)=C^{*}}$ , and ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , the goal node will have a lower f-value and will be expanded before ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, A* never expands nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)>C^{*}}$ .
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Assume there exists an optimal algorithm that expands fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case using the same heuristic.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] That means there must be some node ${\textstyle N'}$ such that ${\textstyle f(N')<C^{*}}$ , yet the algorithm chooses not to expand it.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Now consider a modified graph where a new edge of cost ${\textstyle \varepsilon }$ (with ${\textstyle \varepsilon >0}$ ) is added from ${\textstyle N'}$ to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] If ${\textstyle f(N')+\varepsilon <C^{*}}$ , then the new optimal path goes through ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] However, since the algorithm still avoids expanding ${\textstyle N'}$ , it will miss the new optimal path, violating its optimality.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, no optimal algorithm including A* could expand fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The worst-case complexity of A* is often described as ${\textstyle O(b^{d})}$ , where b is the branching factor and ${\textstyle d}$ is the depth of the shallowest goal.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] While this gives a rough intuition, it does not precisely capture the actual behavior of A*.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A more accurate bound considers the number of nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)\leq C^{*}}$ .
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] This represents both the time and space complexity in the worst case.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] The space complexity of A* is roughly the same as that of all other graph search algorithms, as it keeps all generated nodes in memory.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] In practice, this turns out to be the biggest drawback of the A* search, leading to the development of memory-bounded heuristic searches, such as Iterative deepening A*, memory-bounded A*, and SMA*.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* is often used for the common pathfinding problem in applications such as video games, but was originally designed as a general graph traversal algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] It finds applications in diverse problems, including the problem of parsing using stochastic grammars in NLP.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Other cases include an Informational search with online learning.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] What sets A* apart from a greedy best-first search algorithm is that it takes the cost/distance already traveled, *g*(*n*), into account.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] Some common variants of Dijkstra's algorithm can be viewed as a special case of A* where the heuristic $h(n)=0$ for all nodes; in turn, both Dijkstra and A* are special cases of dynamic programming.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* itself is a special case of a generalization of branch and bound.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* is similar to beam search except that beam search maintains a limit on the numbers of paths that it has to explore.
[src:a-star-search/a-search-algorithm] A* can also be adapted to a bidirectional search algorithm, but special care needs to be taken for the stopping criterion.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] In other words, it should act as a lower bound.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] It is related to the concept of consistent heuristics.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] While all consistent heuristics are admissible, not all admissible heuristics are consistent.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] An admissible heuristic is used to estimate the cost of reaching the goal state in an informed search algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] In order for a heuristic to be admissible to the search problem, the estimated cost must always be lower than or equal to the actual cost of reaching the goal state.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] The search algorithm uses the admissible heuristic to find an estimated optimal path to the goal state from the current node.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] = estimated cost from current node to goal.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] $h(n)$ is calculated using the heuristic function.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] With a non-admissible heuristic, the A* algorithm could overlook the optimal solution to a search problem due to an overestimation in $f(n)$ .
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] An admissible heuristic can be derived from a relaxed version of the problem, or by information from pattern databases that store exact solutions to subproblems of the problem, or by using inductive learning methods.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] The Hamming distance is the total number of misplaced tiles.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] It is clear that this heuristic is admissible since the total number of moves to order the tiles correctly is at least the number of misplaced tiles (each tile not in place must be moved at least once).
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] The cost (number of moves) to the goal (an ordered puzzle) is at least the Hamming distance of the puzzle.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] Consider the puzzle below in which the player wishes to move each tile such that the numbers are ordered.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] The Manhattan distance is an admissible heuristic in this case because every tile will have to be moved at least the number of spots in between itself and its correct position.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] The subscripts show the Manhattan distance for each tile.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] Assume such an algorithm managed to terminate on a path T with a true cost **Ttrue** greater than the optimal path S with true cost **Strue**.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] This means that before terminating, the evaluated cost of T was less than or equal to the evaluated cost of S (or else S would have been picked).
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] Denote these evaluated costs **Teval** and **Seval** respectively.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] If our heuristic is admissible it follows that at this penultimate step **Teval** = **Ttrue** because any increase on the true cost by the heuristic on T would be inadmissible and the heuristic cannot be negative.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] On the other hand, an admissible heuristic would require that **Seval** ≤ **Strue** which combined with the above inequalities gives us **Teval** < **Ttrue** and more specifically **Teval** ≠ **Ttrue**.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] As **Teval** and **Ttrue** cannot be both equal and unequal our assumption must have been false and so it must be impossible to terminate on a more costly than optimal path.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] So clearly we would start off visiting the top middle node, since the expected total cost, i.e. $f(n)$ , is $10+0=10$ .
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] Then the goal would be a candidate, with $f(n)$ equal to $10+100+0=110$ .
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] Then we would clearly pick the bottom nodes one after the other, followed by the updated goal, since they all have $f(n)$ lower than the $f(n)$ of the current goal, i.e. their $f(n)$ is $100,101,102,102$ .
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] So even though the goal was a candidate, we could not pick it because there were still better paths out there.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] This way, an admissible heuristic can ensure optimality.
[src:a-star-search/admissible-heuristic] However, note that although an admissible heuristic can guarantee final optimality, it is not necessarily efficient.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] Some authors have used "best-first search" to refer specifically to a search with a heuristic that attempts to predict how close the end of a path is to a solution (or, goal), so that paths which are judged to be closer to a solution (or, goal) are expanded first.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] This specific type of search is called *greedy best-first search* or *pure heuristic search*.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] Efficient selection of the current best candidate for extension is typically implemented using a priority queue.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] The A* search algorithm is an example of a best-first search algorithm, as is B*.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] Best-first algorithms are often used for path finding in combinatorial search.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] Neither A* nor B* is a greedy best-first search, as they incorporate the distance from the start in addition to estimated distances to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] Using a greedy algorithm, expand the first successor of the parent.
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] Else, the successor is inserted into the queue (in a location determined by its heuristic value).
[src:a-star-search/best-first-search] The procedure will evaluate the remaining successors (if any) of the parent.
