[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] This is achieved by trading optimality, completeness, accuracy, or precision for speed.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] In a way, it can be considered a shortcut.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] A **heuristic function**, also simply called a **heuristic**, is a function that ranks alternatives in search algorithms at each branching step based on available information to decide which branch to follow.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] For example, it may approximate the exact solution.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] The objective of a heuristic is to produce a solution in a reasonable time frame that is good enough for solving the problem at hand.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] This solution may not be the best of all the solutions to this problem, or it may simply approximate the exact solution.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] But it is still valuable because finding it does not require a prohibitively long time.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Heuristics may produce results by themselves, or they may be used in conjunction with optimization algorithms to improve their efficiency (e.g., they may be used to generate good seed values).
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Results about NP-hardness in theoretical computer science make heuristics the only viable option for a variety of complex optimization problems that need to be routinely solved in real-world applications.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Heuristics underlie the whole field of artificial intelligence and the computer simulation of thinking, as they may be used in situations where there are no known algorithms.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] One way of achieving the computational performance gain expected of a heuristic consists of solving a simpler problem whose solution is also a solution to the initial problem.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] so as to select the order to draw using a pen plotter.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] TSP is known to be NP-hard so an optimal solution for even a moderate size problem is difficult to solve.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Instead, the greedy algorithm can be used to give a good but not optimal solution (it is an approximation to the optimal answer) in a reasonably short amount of time.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] The greedy algorithm heuristic says to pick whatever is currently the best next step regardless of whether that prevents (or even makes impossible) good steps later.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] It is a heuristic in the sense that practice indicates it is a good enough solution, while theory indicates that there are better solutions (and even indicates how much better, in some cases).
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Another example of heuristic making an algorithm faster occurs in certain search problems.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Initially, the heuristic tries every possibility at each step, like the full-space search algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] But it can stop the search at any time if the current possibility is already worse than the best solution already found.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] In such search problems, a heuristic can be used to try good choices first so that bad paths can be eliminated early (see alpha–beta pruning).
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] In the case of best-first search algorithms, such as A* search, the heuristic improves the algorithm's convergence while maintaining its correctness as long as the heuristic is admissible.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] In their Turing Award acceptance speech, Allen Newell and Herbert A.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Simon discuss the heuristic search hypothesis: a physical symbol system will repeatedly generate and modify known symbol structures until the created structure matches the solution structure.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Each following step depends upon the step before it, thus the heuristic search learns what avenues to pursue and which ones to disregard by measuring how close the current step is to the solution.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Therefore, some possibilities will never be generated as they are measured to be less likely to complete the solution.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] A heuristic method can accomplish its task by using search trees.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] However, instead of generating all possible solution branches, a heuristic selects branches more likely to produce outcomes than other branches.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] It is selective at each decision point, picking branches that are more likely to produce solutions.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Antivirus software often uses heuristic rules for detecting viruses and other forms of malware.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Heuristic scanning looks for code and/or behavioral patterns common to a class or family of viruses, with different sets of rules for different viruses.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] If a file or executing process is found to contain matching code patterns and/or to be performing that set of activities, then the scanner infers that the file is infected.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] The most advanced part of behavior-based heuristic scanning is that it can work against highly randomized self-modifying/mutating (polymorphic) viruses that cannot be easily detected by simpler string scanning methods.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Heuristic scanning has the potential to detect future viruses without requiring the virus to be first detected somewhere else, submitted to the virus scanner developer, analyzed, and a detection update for the scanner provided to the scanner's users.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Some heuristics have a strong underlying theory; they are either derived in a top-down manner from the theory or are arrived at based on either experimental or real world data.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Others are just rules of thumb based on real-world observation or experience without even a glimpse of theory.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] The latter are exposed to a larger number of pitfalls.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] Statistical analysis can be conducted when employing heuristics to estimate the probability of incorrect outcomes.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] To use a heuristic for solving a search problem or a knapsack problem, it is necessary to check that the heuristic is admissible.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] If a heuristic is not admissible, it may never find the goal, either by ending up in a dead end of graph G or by skipping back and forth between two nodes $v_{i}$ and $v_{j}$ where ${i,j}\neq g$ .
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] The word "heuristic" came into usage in the early 19th century.
[src:a-star-search/heuristic-computer-science] It is formed irregularly from the Greek word *heuriskein*, meaning "to find".
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] The algorithm was first described by Richard E.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Iterative-deepening-A* works as follows: at each iteration, perform a depth-first search, cutting off a branch when its total cost $f(n)=g(n)+h(n)$ exceeds a given *threshold*.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] This threshold starts at the estimate of the cost at the initial state, and increases for each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] At each iteration, the threshold used for the next iteration is the minimum cost of all values that exceeded the current threshold.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] As in A*, the heuristic has to have particular properties to guarantee optimality (shortest paths).
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] for all nodes n, where *h** is the true cost of the shortest path from n to the nearest goal (the "perfect heuristic").
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] IDA* is beneficial when the problem is memory constrained.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] A* search keeps a large queue of unexplored nodes that can quickly fill up memory.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] By contrast, because IDA* does not remember any node except the ones on the current path, it requires an amount of memory that is only linear in the length of the solution that it constructs.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] for all nodes n and all neighbors n' of n; they conclude that compared to a brute-force tree search over an exponential-sized problem, IDA* achieves a smaller search depth (by a constant factor), but not a smaller branching factor.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Recursive best-first search is another memory-constrained version of A* search that can be faster in practice than IDA*, since it requires less regenerating of nodes.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] IDA* relies on iterative deepening using an f -cost threshold that increases each iteration.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Typically, IDA* performs efficiently when the number of nodes expanded in each iteration grows exponentially.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] However, Patrick, Almulla, and Newborn (1992) demonstrated that when the f -cost threshold increases by the smallest possible amount each iteration—such as when f -values are unique and strictly increasing—IDA* expands exactly one additional node per iteration.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Under these worst-case conditions of uniqueness and monotonicity, IDA* expands $N(N+1)/2=\Theta (N^{2})$ nodes, where N is the number of nodes surely-expanded by A*, yielding quadratic complexity compared to A*’s linear $O(N)$ complexity.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] (1992) further showed that this limitation is not exclusive to IDA*: no best-first limited-memory heuristic search algorithm can universally achieve $O(N)$ complexity on trees due to memory constraints.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] They also specify that IDA* achieves $O(N)$ complexity only if the number of iterations with minimal node growth is bounded, a condition not always satisfied.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] To avoid the worst-case scenario, Iterative Budgeted Exponential Search (IBEX) has been introduced in 2019.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] IDA* explores the search space in a depth-first manner and retains no memory of previously expanded nodes beyond the current path.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Consequently, in graphs containing transpositions—where multiple distinct paths lead to the same node—IDA* repeatedly re-expands nodes.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] (1992) illustrated that for directed acyclic graphs, these repeated expansions lead to severe performance degradation, with a worst-case complexity reaching $\Omega (2^{2N})$ , where N is the number of nodes eligible for expansion by A*.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] (1991) also note IDA*’s exponential degradation on graphs compared to A*’s linear $O(N)$ performance under monotone heuristics.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Thus, in scenarios involving transpositions or graph structures, IDA* can be significantly less efficient than A*, suggesting that other graph-search algorithms may be more appropriate choices.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Applications of IDA* are found in such problems as planning.
[src:a-star-search/iterative-deepening-a] Solving the Rubik's Cube is an example of a planning problem that is amenable to solving with IDA*.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] For example, consider navigating a mobile robot inside a building to a distant waypoint.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] It should execute this task while avoiding walls and not falling down stairs.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A motion planning algorithm would take a description of these tasks as input, and produce the speed and turning commands sent to the robot's wheels.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Motion planning algorithms might address robots with a larger number of joints (e.g., industrial manipulators), more complex tasks (e.g. manipulation of objects), different constraints (e.g., a car that can only drive forward), and uncertainty (e.g. imperfect models of the environment or robot).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Motion planning has several robotics applications, such as autonomy, automation, and robot design in CAD software, as well as applications in other fields, such as animating digital characters, video game, architectural design, robotic surgery, and the study of biological molecules.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A basic motion planning problem is to compute a continuous path that connects a start configuration S and a goal configuration G, while avoiding collision with known obstacles.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The robot and obstacle geometry is described in a 2D or 3D *workspace*, while the motion is represented as a path in (possibly higher-dimensional) configuration space.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A configuration describes the pose of the robot, and the configuration space C is the set of all possible configurations.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The set of configurations that avoids collision with obstacles is called the free space Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The complement of Cfree in C is called the obstacle or forbidden region.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Often, it is prohibitively difficult to explicitly compute the shape of Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] However, testing whether a given configuration is in Cfree is efficient.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] First, forward kinematics determine the position of the robot's geometry, and collision detection tests if the robot's geometry collides with the environment's geometry.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Target space is a subspace of free space which denotes where we want the robot to move to.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] In global motion planning, target space is observable by the robot's sensors.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] However, in local motion planning, the robot cannot observe the target space in some states.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] To solve this problem, the robot goes through several virtual target spaces, each of which is located within the observable area (around the robot).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A virtual target space is called a sub-goal.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Obstacle space is a space that the robot can not move to.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Obstacle space is not opposite of free space.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Low-dimensional problems can be solved with grid-based algorithms that overlay a grid on top of configuration space, or geometric algorithms that compute the shape and connectivity of Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Exact motion planning for high-dimensional systems under complex constraints is computationally intractable.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Potential-field algorithms are efficient, but fall prey to local minima (an exception is the harmonic potential fields).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms avoid the problem of local minima, and solve many problems quite quickly.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] They are unable to determine that no path exists, but they have a probability of failure that decreases to zero as more time is spent.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms are currently considered state-of-the-art for motion planning in high-dimensional spaces, and have been applied to problems which have dozens or even hundreds of dimensions (robotic manipulators, biological molecules, animated digital characters, and legged robots).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches overlay a grid on configuration space and assume each configuration is identified with a grid point.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] At each grid point, the robot is allowed to move to adjacent grid points as long as the line between them is completely contained within Cfree (this is tested with collision detection).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] This discretizes the set of actions, and search algorithms (like A*) are used to find a path from the start to the goal.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] These approaches require setting a grid resolution.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Search is faster with coarser grids, but the algorithm will fail to find paths through narrow portions of Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Furthermore, the number of points on the grid grows exponentially in the configuration space dimension, which make them inappropriate for high-dimensional problems.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Traditional grid-based approaches produce paths whose heading changes are constrained to multiples of a given base angle, often resulting in suboptimal paths.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Any-angle path planning approaches find shorter paths by propagating information along grid edges (to search fast) without constraining their paths to grid edges (to find short paths).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches often need to search repeatedly, for example, when the knowledge of the robot about the configuration space changes or the configuration space itself changes during path following.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Incremental heuristic search algorithms replan fast by using experience with the previous similar path-planning problems to speed up their search for the current one.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] These approaches are similar to grid-based search approaches except that they generate a paving covering entirely the configuration space instead of a grid.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The paving is decomposed into two subpavings X−,X+ made with boxes such that X− ⊂ Cfree ⊂ X+.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Characterizing Cfree amounts to solve a set inversion problem.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Interval analysis could thus be used when Cfree cannot be described by linear inequalities in order to have a guaranteed enclosure.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The robot is thus allowed to move freely in X−, and cannot go outside X+.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] To both subpavings, a neighbor graph is built and paths can be found using algorithms such as Dijkstra or A*.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] When a path is feasible in X−, it is also feasible in Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] When no path exists in X+ from one initial configuration to the goal, we have the guarantee that no feasible path exists in Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] As for the grid-based approach, the interval approach is inappropriate for high-dimensional problems, due to the fact that the number of boxes to be generated grows exponentially with respect to the dimension of configuration space.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] An illustration is provided by the three figures on the right where a hook with two degrees of freedom has to move from the left to the right, avoiding two horizontal small segments.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Nicolas Delanoue has shown that the decomposition with subpavings using interval analysis also makes it possible to characterize the topology of Cfree such as counting its number of connected components.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Given a bundle of rays around the current position attributed with their length hitting a wall, the robot moves into the direction of the longest ray unless a door is identified.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Such an algorithm was used for modeling emergency egress from buildings.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] One approach is to treat the robot's configuration as a point in a potential field that combines attraction to the goal, and repulsion from obstacles.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The resulting trajectory is output as the path.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] This approach has advantages in that the trajectory is produced with little computation.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] However, they can become trapped in local minima of the potential field and fail to find a path, or can find a non-optimal path.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The artificial potential fields can be treated as continuum equations similar to electrostatic potential fields (treating the robot like a point charge), or motion through the field can be discretized using a set of linguistic rules.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A navigation function or a probabilistic navigation function are sorts of artificial potential functions which have the quality of not having minimum points except the target point.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A basic algorithm samples N configurations in C, and retains those in Cfree to use as *milestones*.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A roadmap is then constructed that connects two milestones P and Q if the line segment PQ is completely in Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Again, collision detection is used to test inclusion in Cfree.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] To find a path that connects S and G, they are added to the roadmap.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] If a path in the roadmap links S and G, the planner succeeds, and returns that path.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] If not, the reason is not definitive: either there is no path in Cfree, or the planner did not sample enough milestones.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] These algorithms work well for high-dimensional configuration spaces, because unlike combinatorial algorithms, their running time is not (explicitly) exponentially dependent on the dimension of C.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] They are also (generally) substantially easier to implement.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] They are probabilistically complete, meaning the probability that they will produce a solution approaches 1 as more time is spent.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] However, they cannot determine if no solution exists.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Given basic *visibility* conditions on Cfree, it has been proven that as the number of configurations N grows higher, the probability that the above algorithm finds a solution approaches 1 exponentially.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Visibility is not explicitly dependent on the dimension of C; it is possible to have a high-dimensional space with "good" visibility or a low-dimensional space with "poor" visibility.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The experimental success of sample-based methods suggests that most commonly seen spaces have good visibility.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] A motion planner is said to be *complete* if the planner in finite time either produces a solution or correctly reports that there is none.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Most complete algorithms are geometry-based.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The performance of a complete planner is assessed by its computational complexity.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] When proving this property mathematically, one has to make sure, that it happens in finite time and not just in the asymptotic limit.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] This is especially problematic, if there occur infinite sequences (that converge only in the limiting case) during a specific proving technique, since then, theoretically, the algorithm will never stop.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Intuitive "tricks" (often based on induction) are typically mistakenly thought to converge, which they do only for the infinite limit.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] In other words, the solution exists, but the planner will never report it.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] This property therefore is related to Turing completeness and serves in most cases as a theoretical underpinning/guidance.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Planners based on a brute force approach are always complete, but are only realizable for finite and discrete setups.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] In practice, the termination of the algorithm can always be guaranteed by using a counter, that allows only for a maximum number of iterations and then always stops with or without solution.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] For realtime systems, this is typically achieved by using a watchdog timer, that will simply kill the process.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The watchdog has to be independent of all processes (typically realized by low level interrupt routines).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The asymptotic case described in the previous paragraph, however, will not be reached in this way.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] It will report the best one it has found so far (which is better than nothing) or none, but cannot correctly report that there is none.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] All realizations including a watchdog are always incomplete (except all cases can be evaluated in finite time).
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Completeness can only be provided by a very rigorous mathematical correctness proof (often aided by tools and graph based methods) and should only be done by specialized experts if the application includes safety content.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] On the other hand, disproving completeness is easy, since one just needs to find one infinite loop or one wrong result returned.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Formal Verification/Correctness of algorithms is a research field on its own.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] The correct setup of these test cases is a highly sophisticated task.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Many algorithms have been developed to handle variants of this basic problem.
[src:a-star-search/motion-planning] Hybrid systems are those that mix discrete and continuous behavior.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Pathfinding is closely related to the shortest path problem, within graph theory, which examines how to identify the path that best meets some criteria (shortest, cheapest, fastest, etc) between two points in a large network.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] At its core, a pathfinding method searches a graph by starting at one vertex and exploring adjacent nodes until the destination node is reached, generally with the intent of finding the cheapest route.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Although graph searching methods such as a breadth-first search would find a route if given enough time, other methods, which "explore" the graph, would tend to reach the destination sooner.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] An analogy would be a person walking across a room; rather than examining every possible route in advance, the person would generally walk in the direction of the destination and only deviate from the path to avoid an obstruction, and make deviations as minor as possible.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Two primary problems of pathfinding are (1) to find a path between two nodes in a graph; and (2) the shortest path problem—to find the optimal shortest path.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Basic algorithms such as breadth-first and depth-first search address the first problem by exhausting all possibilities; starting from the given node, they iterate over all potential paths until they reach the destination node.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] These algorithms run in $O(|V|+|E|)$ , or linear time, where V is the number of vertices, and E is the number of edges between vertices.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The more complicated problem is finding the optimal path.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The exhaustive approach in this case is known as the Bellman–Ford algorithm, which yields a time complexity of $O(|V||E|)$ , or quadratic time.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] However, it is not necessary to examine all possible paths to find the optimal one.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Algorithms such as A* and Dijkstra's algorithm strategically eliminate paths, either through heuristics or through dynamic programming.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] By eliminating impossible paths, these algorithms can achieve time complexities as low as $O(|E|\log(|V|))$ .
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The above algorithms are among the best general algorithms which operate on a graph without preprocessing.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] However, in practical travel-routing systems, even better time complexities can be attained by algorithms which can pre-process the graph to attain better performance.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] One such algorithm is contraction hierarchies.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A common example of a graph-based pathfinding algorithm is Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This algorithm begins with a start node and an "open set" of candidate nodes.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] At each step, the node in the open set with the lowest distance from the start is examined.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The node is marked "closed", and all nodes adjacent to it are added to the open set if they have not already been examined.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This process repeats until a path to the destination has been found.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Since the lowest distance nodes are examined first, the first time the destination is found, the path to it will be the shortest path.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Dijkstra's algorithm fails if there is a negative edge weight.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] In the hypothetical situation where Nodes A, B, and C form a connected undirected graph with edges AB = 3, AC = 4, and BC = −2, the optimal path from A to C costs 1, and the optimal path from A to B costs 2.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Dijkstra's Algorithm starting from A will first examine B, as that is the closest.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] It will assign a cost of 3 to it, and mark it closed, meaning that its cost will never be reevaluated.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Therefore, Dijkstra's cannot evaluate negative edge weights.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] However, since for many practical purposes there will never be a negative edgeweight, Dijkstra's algorithm is largely suitable for the purpose of pathfinding.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A* is a variant of Dijkstra's algorithm with a wide variety of use cases.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A* assigns a weight to each open node equal to the weight of the edge to that node plus the approximate distance between that node and the finish.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This approximate distance is found by the heuristic, and represents a minimum possible distance between that node and the end.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This allows it to eliminate longer paths once an initial path is found.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] If there is a path of length x between the start and finish, and the minimum distance between a node and the finish is greater than x, that node need not be examined.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A* uses this heuristic to improve on the behavior relative to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] When the heuristic evaluates to zero, A* is equivalent to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] As the heuristic estimate increases and gets closer to the true distance, A* continues to find optimal paths, but runs faster (by virtue of examining fewer nodes).
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] When the value of the heuristic is exactly the true distance, A* examines the fewest nodes.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] In many applications (such as video games) this is acceptable and even desirable, in order to keep the algorithm running quickly.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Pathfinding has a history of being included in video games with moving objects or NPCs.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Chris Crawford in 1982 described how he "expended a great deal of time" trying to solve a problem with pathfinding in *Tanktics*, in which computer tanks became trapped on land within U-shaped lakes.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] "After much wasted effort I discovered a better solution: delete U-shaped lakes from the map", he said.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The concept of hierarchical pathfinding predates its adoption by the video game industry and has its roots in classical artificial intelligence research.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] One of the earliest formal descriptions appears in Sacerdoti's work on ABSTRIPS (Abstraction-Based STRIPS) in 1974, which explored hierarchical search strategies in logic-based planning.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Later research, such as Hierarchical A* by Holte et al., further developed the theory of abstraction hierarchies in search problems.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] In the context of video games, the need for efficient planning on large maps with limited CPU time led to the practical implementation of hierarchical pathfinding algorithms.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A notable advancement was the introduction of Hierarchical Path-Finding A* (HPA*) by Botea et al. in 2004.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] HPA* partitions the map into clusters and precomputes optimal local paths between entrance points of adjacent clusters.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] At runtime, it plans an abstract path through the cluster graph, then refines that path within each cluster.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This significantly reduces the search space and allows for near-optimal planning with much faster performance.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Partial-Refinement A* (PRA*), developed by Sturtevant and Buro, takes a similar approach but emphasizes interleaved planning and acting.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Instead of refining the entire path immediately, PRA* refines only the first few steps and continues refining the rest as needed during execution.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This is especially useful in dynamic environments.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Similar techniques include navigation meshes (navmesh), used for geometric planning in games, and multimodal transportation planning, such as in variations of the travelling salesman problem that involve multiple transport types.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A hierarchical planner performs pathfinding in two phases: first, between clusters at a high level; then, within individual clusters at a low level.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This structure enables guided local search with fewer nodes, resulting in high performance.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The main drawback is the implementation complexity of maintaining abstraction layers and refinements.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A map with a size of 3000×2000 nodes contains 6 million tiles.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Planning a path directly on this scale, even with an optimized algorithm, is computationally intensive due to the vast number of graph nodes and possible paths.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A hierarchical approach divides the map into 300×200 node clusters, forming a 10×10 grid (100 clusters total).
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] The high-level abstract graph now contains only 100 nodes.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A path is planned between these clusters, which is computationally cheap.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Once the abstract path is found, each cluster on the path is processed using a regular A* planner to find the exact low-level route within.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] This two-stage process significantly improves efficiency while maintaining near-optimal path quality.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Multi-agent pathfinding is to find the paths for multiple agents from their current locations to their target locations without colliding with each other, while at the same time optimizing a cost function, such as the sum of the path lengths of all agents.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Many multi-agent pathfinding algorithms are generalized from A*, or based on reduction to other well studied problems such as integer linear programming.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] However, such algorithms are typically incomplete; in other words, not proven to produce a solution within polynomial time.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] Some parallel approaches, such as Collaborative Diffusion, are based on embarrassingly parallel algorithms spreading multi-agent pathfinding into computational grid structures, e.g., cells similar to cellular automata.
[src:a-star-search/pathfinding] A different category of algorithms sacrifice optimality for performance by either making use of known navigation patterns (such as traffic flow) or the topology of the problem space.
